## 1. About this app

The Intrusion Detection System (IDS) StationGuard monitors Ethernet networks in substations and identifies suspicious behavior, prohibited actions, and malfunctions on the IEC 61850 station or process bus.
With this combination of cybersecurity and functional monitoring, not only can new threats and as yet unknown attack scenarios be identified, but different kinds of malfunctions in the substation automation
system too.
This Splunk application does provide an interface from StationGuard to the Splunk SIEM. Visualize the alerts and warnings of all your StationGuard devices in a central location and acheive a better
understanding on what is going on in your monitored networks.

## 2. Requirements

# Data Source

OMICRON StationGuard

# Data Inputs

When installing via Splunkbase, please consider that the TCP / UDP Data Inputs are not included due to the incompatability with Splunk Cloud. Therefore, these Data Inputs have to be added manually, see below.
Please consider, that the current version of this application needs a TCP/UDP port solely for StationGuard devices.
More information about Splunk Data Inputs: https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/SplunkCloud/8.1.2012/Data/Monitordata

Adding data inputs for OMICRON StationGuard:
    - On eligible Universal Forwarders and Single Instances these Data Inputs can be created via opening the Settings → Data Inputs.
    - Depending on the selected protocol for the syslog messages a TCP or UDP data input should be created. To do so, select the according + Add new button.
    - In the next step the port number has to be entered. Optionally a source name override and accepted source IP addresses can be given.
    - In the input settings select for the Source Type in the Network & Security category the omicron_stationguard source type. Do the same for the App Context.	
    - In the last steps review the data and submit the new Data Input.

## 3. Components

# StationGuard System Overview

Dashboard to give an overview of the network state detected by all configured StationGuard devices in your network. This dashboard provides filters for the timeframe, explicit StationGuard devices and alerts which were identified. PLEASE NOTE: These Alerts are not exhaustive and are meant as examples how alerts for StationGuard can look like.

# StationGuard Event Overview

Dashboard to give an overview of the network state detected by all configured StationGuard devices in your network. This dashboard provides filters for the timeframe, explicit StationGuard devices and events which were detected in the monitored networks.

